<h2>What We Look For in Grain-Free Dog Food</h2>

<p>Not all grain-free dog food is created equal. Some brands simply swap wheat for potato starch and call it premium. Here's what separates the genuinely good stuff from the marketing fluff:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Meat content above 50%</strong> — the whole point of grain-free is better ingredients. If meat isn't the majority, what are you paying for?</li>
  <li><strong>Named meat sources</strong> — "meat meal" could be anything. Look for "chicken", "salmon", "turkey" with percentages listed.</li>
  <li><strong>Quality carbohydrates</strong> — sweet potato and peas beat white potato and tapioca. Slow-release energy matters.</li>
  <li><strong>No artificial preservatives</strong> — BHA, BHT, and ethoxyquin have no place in premium food.</li>
  <li><strong>Transparent labelling</strong> — if a brand won't tell you exactly what's in the bag, that's a red flag.</li>
</ul>

